\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
CUGEL marched along the foreshore, shivering to the bite of the wind. The landscape was barren and dreary; to the left, black waves broke over the mud-flats; to the right, a line of low hills barred access to inland regions.}{
\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }\pard \ql \fi360\li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12867288 {\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
Cugel's mood was bleak. He carried neither terces nor so much as a sharp stick to protect himself against footpads. Slime from the mud-flats squelched in his boots and his sodden garments smelled of marine decay.}{
\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 At a tidal pool Cugel rinsed 
out his boots and thereafter walked more comfortably, though the slime still made a mockery of style and dignity. Hunching along the shore Cugel resembled a great bedraggled bird.}{\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 Where a sluggish river seeped into the sea, Cugel came upon an old road, which might well lead to the village Tustvold, and the possibility of food and shelter. Cugel turned inland, away from the shore.}{
\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 To keep himself warm Cugel began to trot and jog, with knees jerking high. So passed a mile or two, and the hills gave way to a c
urious landscape of cultivated fields mingled with areas of wasteland. In the distance steep-sided knolls rose at irregular intervals, like islands in a sea of air.}{\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 No human habitation could be seen, but in the fields groups of women tended broad-beans and
 millet. As Cugel jogged past, they raised from their work to stare. Cugel found their attention offensive, and ran proudly past, looking neither right nor left.}{\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 Clouds sliding over the hills f}{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid6844166 rom the we}{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 st cooled the air and seemed to presage rain. Cugel s
earched ahead for the village Tustvold, without success. The clouds drifted across the sun, darkening the already wan light, and the landscape took on the}{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid6844166  }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
semblance of an ancient sepia painting, with flat perspectives and the pungko trees superimposed like scratchings of black ink.}{\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 A shaft of sunlight struck through the clouds, to play upon a cluster of white columns, at a distance of something over a mile.}{\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 Cugel stopped short to stare at the odd array. A temple? A mausoleum? The ruins of an enormous palace
