\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 Crouching, keeping to the cover of trees and shrubbery, Cugel approached the manse. With cat-like stealth he sidled to a window and peered within.}{\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 At a table, reading from a yellow-leafed boo
k, sat a man of indeterminate age, stoop-shouldered and bald except for a fringe of brown-gray hair. A long nose hooked from his rather squat head, with protuberant milky golden eyes close-set to either side. His arms and legs were long and angular; he wo
re a black velvet suit and rings on every finger, save the forefingers where he wore three. In repose his face seemed calm and easy, and Cugel looked in vain for what he considered the signals of depravity.}{\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 

\par }{\b0\f54\fs24\cf1\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 Cugel surveyed the room and its contents. On a sid
eboard rested a miscellany of curios and oddments: a pyramid of black stone, a coil of rope, glass bottles, small masks hanging on a board, stacked books, a zither, a brass instrument of many arcs and beams, a bouquet of flowers carved from stone.}{
\b0\f54\fs24\insrsid4274412\charrsid3035278 
